{"cursor":"21730","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nThe 'right of self-defense (according to U.S. law)' (also called, when it\napplies to the defense of another, 'alter ego defense', 'defense of others',\n'defense of a third person') is the right for civilians acting on their own\nbehalf to engage in a level of violence, called 'reasonable force' or 'defensive\nforce', for the sake of defending one's own life or the lives of others,\nincluding, in certain circumstances, the use of deadly force.\n","linknr":323,"url":"Right_of_self-defense","recorded":1362546703,"links":46,"instances":["australia","legal_system","united_states","polity"],"pdf":["http://wwwdata.unibg.it/dati/bacheca/567/18910.pdf"],"categories":["Civil and political rights","Human rights","Self-defense"],"headings":["Theory","Legal status of self-defense","Defense of others","Definition in specific countries","See also","References","Bibliography","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bd/Ambox_globe_content.svg/48px-Ambox_globe_content.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/f2/Edit-clear.svg/40px-Edit-clear.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4c/Wikisource-logo.svg/12px-Wikisource-logo.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["state","polity"],["civil_law","legal_system"],["self-defence","australia"],["self-defense","sweden"],["self-defense","united_states"]],"members":["civil_law","state"],"related":["Deadly_force","Civil_defense","Roman_law","Hobbes","State_of_nature","John_Locke","Sovereignty